library org.openxtalk.library.torrent

-- torrent.lcb - the LCB binding for TorrentXT (library
-- org.openxtalk.library.torrent). It declares one `private foreign handler`
-- per btx_* symbol in src/btx_abi.h and wraps each in a `public bt*` handler
-- that hides every handle, pre-sizes and reuses the poll/status buffers, walks
-- the big-endian KV records by byte arithmetic, and never throws into script.
--
-- The FFI idiom for byte buffers. An LCB Data does NOT auto-bridge to a C
-- `void*` (the Language Reference is explicit: "No automatic bridging from Data
-- or String to Pointer exists" - a Data marshals as an MCDataRef). So, matching
-- the proven htmltidy/HIDAPI bindings:
--   * OUTPUT buffers (C fills them) are raw blocks from the engine <builtin>
--     MCMemoryAllocate, passed as a real Pointer. C returns bytes-written (or the
--     negative of the capacity it needed, so we grow and retry), then we copy the
--     written bytes back into a Data with MCDataCreateWithBytes and walk them.
--   * INPUT buffers (C reads them) pass MCDataGetBytePtr(theData) - the read-only
--     pointer to a Data's own bytes - together with `the number of bytes in` it.
--   * records are walked with `the code of (byte I of D)` (big-endian u16) and
--     `byte X to Y of D` for sub-ranges - exactly midi.lcb's `midiPoll`.
--   * every foreign call sits inside `unsafe ... end unsafe`; all `variable`s
--     are declared at the top of their handler.
--
-- The numeric constants below MIRROR src/btx_record.h; tools/check-record-
-- registry.py proves they never drift. 64-bit values and info-hashes cross as
-- ASCII (an LCB number is a double, so a 64-bit int would lose precision) - we
-- keep them as their decoded String, which is lossless for display.
--
-- Runtime behaviour needs an OXT pass to confirm (OXT cannot compile/run .lcb
-- headlessly); the static gate tools/check-livecodescript.py is run on every
-- edit. If `textDecode`/byte-chunk operators fail to resolve in a given OXT
-- build, add `use com.livecode.byte` alongside the foreign import below.

use com.livecode.foreign

metadata version is "0.1.0"
metadata author is "Seth Morrow Software"
metadata title is "TorrentXT"

-- ===================================================================== --
--  Constants
-- ===================================================================== --

-- Must equal BTX_ABI_VERSION in src/btx_abi.h; _checkABI() throws on skew.
constant kABIVersion is 4

-- libfoundation MCStringEncoding value for UTF-8 (ASCII=0, Windows1252=1,
-- MacRoman=2, ISO8859_1=3, UTF8=4). Used by _decodeText via MCStringDecode.
constant kEncodingUtf8 is 4

-- torrent_flags_t bit VALUES (stable libtorrent constants; mirror of
-- libtorrent/torrent_flags.hpp). Passed to btSetTorrentFlags / btUnsetTorrentFlags
-- as decimal strings. Combine by adding the values (the bits are disjoint).
constant kFlagSeedMode is "1"             -- bit 0:  assume we already have all data
constant kFlagUploadMode is "2"           -- bit 1:  upload only, never request
constant kFlagShareMode is "4"            -- bit 2:  optimise for share-ratio
constant kFlagApplyIpFilter is "8"        -- bit 3:  subject this torrent to the IP filter
constant kFlagPaused is "16"              -- bit 4:  start paused
constant kFlagAutoManaged is "32"         -- bit 5:  let libtorrent queue/start/stop it
constant kFlagSuperSeeding is "256"       -- bit 8:  super-seed (initial-seed) mode
constant kFlagSequentialDownload is "512" -- bit 9:  download pieces in order (streaming)
constant kFlagStopWhenReady is "1024"     -- bit 10: pause as soon as checking finishes

-- Reusable buffer capacities (the single-thread performance playbook: allocate
-- once, reuse every poll, never rebuild). Grown on demand if the shim reports a
-- bigger -needed.
constant kDrainCap is 65536
constant kStatusCap is 8192
constant kScratchCap is 512

-- Record field value types (mirror btx_record.h FieldType -> kType*).
constant kTypeInt is 0
constant kTypeReal is 1
constant kTypeUtf8 is 2
constant kTypeRaw is 3
constant kTypeHex is 4

